Sorry to tell you, but you are wrong. Timerefresh renders 360 images, turning
the view around. Although, in GLQuake, it seem like it doesn't draw if it is
incorrectly configured. Again, try my gl.cfg file and do timerefresh again.
The problem is that it only test the speed from the current view, so you would
have to do timerefresh in a lot of rooms, and take the average. Timedemo is
more incorrect. As demoplaying causes disk access and GLQuake seem to have
some very small file buffers, framerate drops to ~half because of context
switches.

