Am 10-M=E4r-00 schrieb Mr.Return:

>Hans-Joerg Frieden wrote:

>> You  can  pass individual  triangles  using multiple  W3D_DrawTriangle
>> calls  only. For strips  and fans,  there is  the W3D_DrawTriStrip/Fan
>> functions that really do use the feature of drawing continously if the
>> chip supports it.

>Ok, that`s clear. But does the Permedia support it ? The main question
>is if I can tell the Permedia to draw a number of triangles while I
>calculate the next ones. Giving him a fan/strip would do the job.

It wouldn't do.

My suggestion for everyone is to completely forget about anything
concerning parallelism when talking about 3d hardware rendering. It
complicates application design and doesn't give any advantage (but
might even be disadvantageous). Even if you provide a huge triangle
strip to W3D/the driver, the function will not return before at least
n-1 triangles are drawn. The Permedia2 doesn't process strips/fans
directly as a whole (that would probably require some DMA-based
approach), but it allows the driver to only specify the new vertices
of a strip rather than requiring to provide all three vertices for
each triangle in the strip/fan. In other words: drawing strips/fans
is internally a loop, where in every iteration a new vertex is
specified and the next triangle-draw operation is triggered by the
driver. You simply can't use any kind of parallelism.

bye
