It's written above. Either you really know how to program in PPC ASM
and then you should be able to write that code, otherwise you should
REALLY switch to a mixture of C and ASM.

The Warp3D functions are documented, so you know which parameters
you have to provide for every function. I already told you that
parameters are passed from r3 upwards (2nd parameter in r4, 3rd parameter
in r5 etc.). You certainly have the library base somewhere, as you
have to open Warp3DPPC.library using exec/OpenLibrary. With the library
base you can read out the function address, because you know the LVO
of the function to call. So all you have to do is filling the registers,
evaluate the function address (LibraryBase+LVO+2, with LVO beeing negativ=
e),
put it into the link register and do a 'BLRL'.

Maybe you didn't realize yet that Warp3DPPC.library is exactly the same
as Warp3D.library? All documentation of Warp3D applies to both libraries.
In C there is absolutely no difference at all at source level (except
for the OpenLibrary call).

bye
