@node 08109.007
Subject: Games on the Amiga
From: Hans-Joerg Frieden <hfrieden@uni-trier.de>
Date: Tue, 14 Mar 2000 15:31:25 +0100 (CET)

Hi! 

In the recent past I  have read many remarks about Hyperion's strategy
of porting  games instead  of developing original  games. I  will post
this one  statement about it,  which, BTW, reflects my  own *personal*
opinion  on the  matter, and  should not  be taken  representative for
either Hyperion or the Warp3D team  - all of which can prefectly speak
for themselves.  (if someone  wants to  put this on  his web  page, go
ahead!)

People tend to think that only new development will convince people to
abandon their  PC or Mac  and change over  to the Amiga. They  tend to
think  that original  developent is  what  could save  the Amiga  from
extinction. 

They  tend  to overlook  the  point  that  original development  takes
considerably longer than porting. Furthermore, the result might not be
what you  are looking for. It  is very unlikely that  anything that an
Amiga company  may produce  right now (with  our limited  personal and
financial resources) can come only  close to what the PC gaming market
has to  offer now; and  this is not  taking into account what  will be
available in, say two or three years. There is too much key technology
missing on the Amiga, not only in the graphics department (look at the
Demos available for the GeForce  graphics chip), but also in the terms
of CPU power, Sound capabilities, memory configurations, you name it. 

Right now, the major problem is that the Amiga is lacking software. It
is lacking software  for the older machines, and even  more so for the
current PPC-Based  machines. Many people are abandoning  the Amiga for
these reasons; many people argue that even with the release of new (G3
or G4) hardware, the software situation isn't going to change. 

Just have  a look around. Look  at, for example,  Explorer 2260, which
was at one point  a reason for *me* to want a PPC.  But the game is in
development for  so long now  (no pun intended,  Ed and Chris  and all
folks at TWF,  I *know* it takes  ages to make a good  game) that some
people will not be ready to  wait any longer for the release when they
see  the  first trailer  movies  from  Freespace  2 or  Starlancer  or
whatever. 

The  goal  *right  now*  must  be  to keep  Amiga  people  with  their
Amiga. We're  not at all  in a situation  where we can aim  at pulling
over  people  from other  platforms,  we're  struggling  for the  very
survival of  our platform - a platfrom  which I love so  dearly that I
would call it a very sad day when I would need to leave it behind. The
goal  *right now*  must be  to  give current  PPC owners  a reason  to
believe that their  machine *can* do all the stuff,  and give them the
feeling that their money wasn't  spend on expensive gadgets, plus give
non-PPC owning people a reason to upgrade their machines. 

Only when the  Amiga has recovered from its current  drop can we think
about   making  the   platform   attractive  for   gamers from   other
systems.  Only  then can  original development be  used to  make other
games look over  to our system and say, "hey, that's  one game I would
really like to play"... 

One  last  thing:  People  said  that  our games  are  too  old.  This
definately depends on  what you call old, but I would  not call an end
of '98 title that is still  being played on the internet and old game.
Apart from that, I advise you  to study the new issue of Amiga Format;
sometimes the hints are as clear as a picture...


Regards, Hans-Joerg.

