@node 08121.003
Subject: Re: Chroma testing?
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Mon, 27 Mar 2000 12:30:58 +0200

Am 26-M=E4r-00 schrieb Tim Hanson:

>Hi All,
>Can someone explain chroma testing to me? Specifically what the paramete=
rs
for
>W3D_SetChromaTestBounds mean.

>I think I`ve got the gist but how should I set the upper and lower
parameters?
>These are color values of some sort I presume but in what format?

All three RGB components define a range from 0 to 255 (resp. 0 to 1.0
in floating point format). The parameters for SetChromaTestBounds define
a subrange inside this range (for every component), which defines the
texture color values to be masked out when painting a texture. It's like
ZBuffering with the difference that pixels aren't masked out due to
depth value, but due to the texel colors. Additionally the Z buffer
isn't updated, if a texel is masked out.

In most cases the effect is used to implement binary transparency
(visible/not visible) without having to worry about problems with
zbuffering. You can draw the polygons in whatever order you like
it will come out right. The feature was added when it turned out that
WO2097 would benefit of it. Without chroma testing transparency
sometimes doesn't work right in WO2097.

